    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-01-16T20:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-01-16T20:00:00-05:00" n="567"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d567">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.74/803: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-01-16T20:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 16, 1928—8 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>19. Your telegrams No. 1, January 3, 2 p.m., and No. 27, January 13, 6 p.m.</p>
                <p>1. The following paragraph from the Department’s note of January 12, 1928, to the
                    British Ambassador is quoted:</p>
                <p>[Here follows the text of the fourth paragraph of the note printed on <ref
                        target="#pg_558">page 558</ref>.]</p>
                <p>This may be used by you as you see fit, but you should guard against a possible
                    inference that this Government, in thus stating its position, abandons in any
                    way the existing contract rights of American citizens.</p>
                <p>2. Unless it be that Ginman desires the Chinese to infer that this Government
                    favors an international understanding without participation by the Chinese, the
                    Department perceives no reason for <pb facs="0679" n="561" xml:id="pg_561"/> an
                    informal conference in regard to wireless matters between yourself and the
                    British and Japanese Ministers as requested by Ginman. It is asserted by Radio
                    Corporation that Ginman, who now asserts that he suspects the Japanese, was
                    undoubtedly the person who arranged in 1921 joint Japanese, British, and French
                    opposition to the Federal Wireless contract.<note n="37" xml:id="d567fn37">See
                            <ref target="frus1921v01#pg_404">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1921, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, pp. 404</ref> ff.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Olds</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
